  "prompt": "What are the best small classes for freshmen at Southern Connecticut State?",
  "response": "As of my last update in October 2023, I don't have access to specific course offerings or reviews for small classes at Southern Connecticut State University (SCSU). However, here are a few general tips to help freshmen find the best small classes:\n\n1. **First-Year Experience (FYE) Courses**: Many universities offer first-year experience courses designed to help freshmen transition into college life. These classes are typically smaller and focus on developing academic and social skills.\n\n2. **Honors Program**: If you are eligible, consider joining the Honors Program. Honors courses often have smaller class sizes and provide a more intimate and engaging learning environment.\n\n3. **Seminar Courses**: Look for seminar-style classes. These are usually designed to be smaller and more discussion-based, providing a more personalized learning experience.\n\n4. **Department Recommendations**: Consult with academic advisors or department heads. They can often recommend smaller classes that are highly regarded by students.\n\n5. **Special Topics Courses**: These courses often have smaller enrollments and focus on specific themes or issues, providing a unique and engaging learning experience.\n\n6. **Upper-Level Courses**: Sometimes, upper-level courses might have smaller class sizes. Check if there are any introductory courses in your major that are available to freshmen.\n\n7. **Language Classes**: Introductory language classes tend to have smaller class sizes to facilitate better learning and participation.\n\n8. **Creative Arts Courses**: Classes in areas such as art, music, theater, and writing often have smaller class sizes to provide hands-on learning experiences.\n\nTo get the most current and specific recommendations, I suggest reaching out to academic advisors at SCSU or checking the university\u2019s course catalog and student reviews.",
